<BYLINE>
<P>
By ZAN STEWART 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * * * 1/2 Brian Lynch, "Live at the Main Event," Criss Cross. This is a gutsy, 
flavorful date, spotlighting the ex-Art Blakey, now Phil Woods trumpeter, whose 
tone snaps and pops, and whose lyricism is compelling.Also featured is organist 
Melvin Rhyne, whose sound -- open yet subtle -- recalls the late Larry Young. 
The two, plus saxman Ralph Moore, guitarist Peter Bernstein and drummer Kenny 
Washington, vigorously interpret Rhyne's tasty, Latin-ish "Nite 'Vidual I," 
Horace Silver's flowing "Ecaroh" and Arthur Hamilton's classic ballad "Cry Me a 
River." A class effort all around, and you'll have to turn over a lot of rocks 
to find a blues cliche. 
</P>
<P>
 New albums are rated on a scale of one star (poor), two stars (fair), three 
stars (good) and four stars (excellent). ZAN STEWART 
