<HEADLINE>
<P>
MIXED MEDIA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS WILLMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 "DEVO: THE COMPLETE TRUTH ABOUT DE-EVOLUTION" 
</P>
<P>
 Devo 
</P>
<P>
 Voyager laser disc , $49.95 
</P>
<P>
 * * * * 
</P>
<P>
 Prescient as the Akron, Ohio, band proved, Devo was wrong on one score: 
Evolution continues, at least for videophiles who've given up low-on-the-ladder 
VHS for the digital superiority of laser discs. And as pop music goes, this is 
the format's most visionary application yet.The complete catalogue of Devo 
videos from the mid-'70s on (the early groundbreaking ones still being 
spookiest and best) is only the beginning. You also get a separate audio 
commentary track and still-frame text in which the head spuds wax historical 
and funnily bitter about their experiences with everyone from David Bowie and 
Eno to assorted record company weasels. 
</P>
<P>
 Items in this periodic survey of pop-related books, videocassettes and laser 
discs are rated on a scale of one star (poor) to four (excellent). CHRIS 
WILLMAN 
</P>
