<HEADLINE>
<P>
APPLIANCE CHECK BY GAS CO. COULD PREVENT TRAGEDY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GARY ABRAMS, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES, Abrams is a licensed general contractor 
who writes on home improvement topics for The Times. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It is a tragedy that occurs every year in Southern California. We see it on 
the evening news . . . a family is asphyxiated in their sleep from poisonous 
fumes emitted by a faulty gas furnace. 
</P>
<P>
 Sadly, almost every such tragedy we hear about is preventable by simply 
contacting the Southern California Gas Co. to arrange a free safety check of 
your gas appliances. 
</P>
<P>
 Although it is not widely publicized, the Gas Co. suggests that homeowners and 
renters call their number, listed in the local white pages, to have a 
technician come for an inspection at least once a year. 
</P>
<P>
 The service person will check for proper venting, gas leakage, burner 
operation and firebox cracks. 
</P>
<P>
 Any problems he or she detects will likely not be solvable on the spot as the 
Gas Co. does not do repair work. 
</P>
<P>
 Instead they may issue a "notice of unsatisfactory condition," which requires 
you to have a licensed contractor make repairs. 
</P>
<P>
 Of course, if this occurs you may be inconvenienced by not having use of the 
appliance until repairs are completed, but you may be preventing a tragedy at 
the same time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
