<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE FEAR CRIME REGARDLESS OF SOURCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * Re: Sam Enriquez's "Middle Class Despairs Over Paradise Lost," (Dec. 19). 
</P>
<P>
 Enriquez correctly identifies the Valley's shrinking white majority but 
incorrectly identifies vanishing jobs and rising crime as a white problem.It is 
everyone's problem. 
</P>
<P>
 Throughout Enriquez's article, the most basic complaint is about Valley crime. 
</P>
<P>
 I am Latino and lived much of my childhood in one of Los Angeles' poorer 
neighborhoods -- one of those neighborhoods that Angelenos avoid. However, I 
remember that in the 1950s and early 1960s, not one of our neighbors locked 
their doors. Leaving the house meant that you locked the front door but the 
back door remained unlocked. In those days, poor just meant poor. Poor did not 
mean crime. 
</P>
<P>
 The overwhelming majority of people couldn't care less if a black, white or 
Latino person lives next door. The vast majority of people actually welcome the 
diversity. They hate and fear the crime, whomever it comes from. 
</P>
<P>
 ROBERT A. CLANDOS 
</P>
<P>
 Calabasas 
</P>
