<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEALS / ALLAN SLOAN: AMID THE SMILES, UNITED'S PROPOSAL ELICITS ONE FROWN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN SLOAN , ALLAN SLOAN is a financial columnist for Newsday in New York. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Questioning the proposed deal between United Airlines and its employees is 
almost like spitting on Mom and apple pie. United employees are cutting their 
own pay and making big concessions on work rules in return for a majority stake 
in the airline. It's being touted as the trend-setting deal of the 90s. It's 
been blessed by United's board and leaders of two of the company's three major 
unions, and the Clinton Administration has praised it to the skies. 
</P>
<P>
 But when you look at the actual deal, disclosed in a huge and boring 
Securities and Exchange Commission filing, it looks more like Mom made her pie 
out of rotten apples. You see a deal supposedly worth more than $8 billion 
that, despite the unions' contribution, is being balanced on the backs of 
United's current stockholders and you, the taxpaying public. 
</P>
<P>
 My problem isn't that employees are getting a piece of the action. My problem 
is that they're getting majority ownership before paying for it. And that many 
of the United people who did this deal will be paid richly to leave. Talk about 
your friendly skies. 
</P>
<P>
 Let's start with the terms of the deal itself. It calls for United to give 
holders $743 million of its surplus cash and a total of $1.8 billion of newly 
issued promissory notes and preferred stock. In all, $88 a share. Holders will 
also get one share of New United, which the unions value at $85. The company 
hasn't valued it; I think $85 is too high. But let's use $85, do the math and 
-- tadah! -- current shareholders are getting $5 billion, of which $4.25 
billion is paper. All told, a claimed $173 per share for a stock selling in the 
$140s. 
</P>
<P>
 Okay. Now, Employee Stock Ownership Plans created for the occasion fork over 
around $3.5 billion to $4 billion in return for preferred stock convertible 
into 53% to 63% of New United's stock. In other words, majority ownership. But 
are the ESOPs using money? Don't be silly -- they don't have it. They're using 
promissory notes. 
</P>
<P>
 Now, watch. United makes contributions to the ESOPs, which give the money back 
to United to pay off their promissory notes. Why this nonsensical shuffling? 
Taxes. United's contributions to the ESOPs are tax-deductible, but the payments 
it gets back from the ESOPs aren't taxable. So United ends up with both the 
cash and a tax deduction. Pretty slick. 
</P>
<P>
 Say there are $4 billion of deductions -- the union projects more than that. 
At today's tax rates, those deductions save United $1.4 billion. Thank you, 
taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
 So there you have it -- $5 billion of supposed value to today's stockholders, 
another $3.5 billion or so from United employees. An $8-billion-plus deal, with 
only $743 million of cash. And no mean, nasty lenders to foreclose if something 
goes wrong. Who says LBOs are dead? 
</P>
<P>
 But I don't think the underlying assumptions fly. The value of the labor 
concessions -- put at 4.5 billion of today's dollars by the company and $6 
billion by the unions -- is highly inflated. It assumes that without a deal, 
United would continue as is for 12 years. But employees would have to give up 
something even without this deal, because otherwise, United won't stay alive 
for anything like 12 years. So the workers are getting credit for some 
concessions they would have to make anyway. 
</P>
<P>
 United's workers get a lot more for bowing to the inevitable than workers at 
other airlines got. TWA and Northwest, for instance, which were at death's door 
and whose stock was worth virtually nothing, gave workers less than a majority 
in return for save-the-day concessions. 
</P>
<P>
 Clearly, United's employees deserve a piece of the action in return for what 
they're giving up. But a majority stake worth billions of dollars? 
</P>
<P>
 United's explanation, delivered in background discussions: The unions were 
determined to get a majority stake, and United didn't want to risk a 
catastrophic showdown.  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 I'll bet this cave-in reflects deep pessimism among United's top managers and 
its board about the airline business, in which no one but Southwest Airlines 
ever seems to have ever made any real money or to have any hope of making any. 
This way, United's top honchos will declare victory and hit the silk. What 
happens later won't be their fault. 
</P>
<P>
 Many juicy details haven't been worked out yet. I can't wait to see how United 
handles Chairman Stephen Wolf's stock options, many of which have exercise 
prices well above the $173 a share at which the unions value this deal. 
</P>
<P>
 I'm also eager to see what the directors give themselves; the aborted 1989 
union takeover would have given them 10 years' fees and lifetime free United 
tickets.  
</P>
<P>
 The 1989 deal, whose collapse clobbered the stock market, was financially 
insane. But at least it was fair to stockholders, who would have gotten cash. 
Here, they're expected to take mostly paper, while turning over control. (The 
unions, by the way, dispute that; they claim the managers they hire will run 
New United without having to look over their shoulders.) 
</P>
<P>
 For all the drumbeating, one constituency still hasn't been wooed: United 
stockholders, who have to approve the deal. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm waiting to be convinced," says John Neff of Boston-based Wellington 
Management, United's biggest holder with just under 10% of its stock. Neff, who 
runs the well-known Windsor Fund, said in an interview that the offer "seems to 
be on the light side, considering that it involves selling control of the 
company."  
</P>
<P>
 Maybe when all the details emerge, even skeptics like me will be convinced 
this deal is wonderful. But I doubt it. Apple pie is one thing. But pie in the 
face is quite another. 
</P>
</TEXT>
